Consider the following grammar G over terminals {if, then, else, id, ;} :

S → if id then S else S | id ;

(i) [2 marks] Show that this grammar is ambiguous by constructing two distinct parse trees for the string: if id then if id then id ; else id ;

(ii) [3 marks] Give a disambiguated version of this grammar that implements the 'dangling else' rule (else binds to the nearest unmatched if), and verify your solution produces only one parse tree for the above string.

Consider the following C code:

int *p = malloc(10 * sizeof(int));
int *q = p + 5;
free(p);
q[0] = 42;  // Line X

Is the assignment at Line X undefined behaviour? Justify your answer with reference to the C standard's memory model.

A programmer writes:

char buffer[100];
char *ptr = buffer;
ptr += 1000000;

Explain whether this code exhibits undefined behaviour. What assumptions about memory layout might this code violate?

Consider the following C code:
```c
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int) * 10);
int *q = p + 5;
free(p);
int x = *q;
```
Explain what undefined behaviour may occur here and why this code is dangerous even though q still points to memory that was allocated.

Consider the following C code:
```c
int *p = malloc(sizeof(int));
*p = 42;
free(p);
*p = 100;
```
Explain what undefined behaviour occurs in this code and why this is dangerous. What would be a safer approach?

Consider the following C code:
```c
int x = 5;
int *p = &x;
int **q = &p;
```
Explain what happens to the values and addresses involved. What would be the result of `**q`?

Consider the following C code:
  int *p = malloc(sizeof(int) * 10);
  free(p);
  p[5] = 42;
Explain what undefined behaviour is occurring here and why this code is dangerous even if it appears to work.

Consider the following C code:

struct Node {
  int data;
  struct Node *next;
};

struct Node *p = malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
p->data = 5;
p->next = NULL;

Explain what happens when you access p->data versus (*p).data. Are these equivalent? Justify your answer.

Write a C function that safely concatenates two strings without buffer overflow:

char* safe_concat(const char *s1, const char *s2);

Your implementation should allocate appropriate memory dynamically and handle edge cases (NULL pointers, empty strings). Explain any assumptions you make about memory management.

Define the Chomsky Hierarchy and identify which class of language each of the following belongs to. Justify your answers.
(i) L₁ = {aⁿbⁿcⁿ : n ≥ 0}
(ii) L₂ = {ww : w ∈ {a,b}*}
(iii) L₃ = {aⁿbᵐ : n,m ≥ 0}

Define the Chomsky hierarchy and identify which language class each of the following belongs to. Justify your answers:
(i) L₁ = {aⁿbⁿcⁿ | n ≥ 0}
(ii) L₂ = {ww | w ∈ {a,b}*}
(iii) L₃ = {a*b*c*}

Using resolution theorem proving, show that the following goal logically follows from statements 1–3 (in isolation): "If a member has paid their fee and a book is not borrowed, then that member can borrow that book."

Your answer should:
(i) Negate the goal and convert it to clausal form;
(ii) Exhibit a resolution derivation of the empty clause (or explain why none exists);
(iii) Identify the most general unifiers used at each resolution step.
